<b>Put-in:</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
Barnard, NC
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
<b>Take-out:</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
Hot Springs, NC
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
<b>Directions from Asheville (to take-out):</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
43 minutes.&Acirc;&nbsp; Head north out of Asheville on US
19/23.&Acirc;&nbsp; Take the US 25/70 (Marshall) exit.&Acirc;&nbsp; Follow
US 25/70 all the way to the outskirts of Hot Springs (this will require
making a left turn to cross the Big Laurel -- if you are a typical paddler
you will park after making the turn and check the gauge painted on river
left beneath the bridge).&Acirc;&nbsp; Just before crossing the bridge into
town, turn right, then left to go under the bridge and upstream to the
rafting outpost parking area.
<p>
Directions to the alternate take-out at Stackhouse:&Acirc;&nbsp; Head
north out of Asheville on US 19/23.&Acirc;&nbsp; Take the US 25/70
(Marshall) exit.&Acirc;&nbsp; Follow US 25/70 19 miles to State Road
1139/1319 (Stackhouse Road).&Acirc;&nbsp; Look for it on your left
shortly after you pass USA Raft.&Acirc;&nbsp; Turn left and follow
Stackhouse Road downhill all the way to the river.
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
<b>Shuttle:</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
20 minutes each way.&Acirc;&nbsp; Retrace your steps back to the
&quot;T&quot; intersection after the bridge over the Big
Laurel.&Acirc;&nbsp; Turn right with US 25/70 to continue retracing your
steps all the way to the State Road 1151 (Barnard Road).&Acirc;&nbsp; Turn
right onto Barnard Road and follow it downhill all the way to the river (be
alert, there are some twists and turns).&Acirc;&nbsp; The put-in is on
river right just upstream of the bridge.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
<b>Other access points:</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
Stackhouse, hike into Frank Bell&#39;s Rapid, others
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
<b>Camping:</b>
</td>
<td colspan="2" width="80%">
There are camping and lodging opportunities aplenty in Hot
Springs.&Acirc;&nbsp; My family and I like the <b><a href="http://www.cs.unca.edu/nfsnc/recreation/RockyBluff.pdf" target="_blank">Rocky Bluff</a></b> USFS Campground (828-622-3202;&Acirc;&nbsp;
open the Rocky Bluff file with the free <a href="http://www.adobe.com/products/acrobat/readstep.html" target="_blank">adobe
acrobat reader</a>).&Acirc;&nbsp; Open May 1 to October 31, this campground
has a short nature trail running alongside Spring Creek.&Acirc;&nbsp; To
get there, take NC 209 South three miles out of town, heading toward the
put-in for Spring Creek.&Acirc;&nbsp; Campsites cost $8 a
night.&Acirc;&nbsp; To learn more, check out <a href="http://www.gorp.com/dow/southern/pisgcmp.htm#rocky%20bluff" target="_blank">Gorp&#39;s Rocky Bluff</a> page.&Acirc;&nbsp; Other campgrounds
include the <a href="http://www.hotspringsspa-nc.com/campground/body_campground.html" target="_blank">Hot Springs Campground</a>, conveniently located on the river and
the USFS&#39;s <b>Silvermine Group Campground</b> (828-622-3202).
<p>
There are many, many rustic bed and breakfasts in Hot
Springs.&Acirc;&nbsp; I know several paddlers who have been married at
<a href="http://www.bbonline.com/nc/ducketthouse/" target="_blank">The
Duckett House</a>, for example, and another couple who were married on
<a href="http://ncnatural.com/NCUSFS/Pisgah/fbroad.html" target="_blank">Max Patch</a> but had their reception at the Rock
House.&Acirc;&nbsp; The most unique bed and breakfast, however, has to be
Elmer Hall&#39;s <b>Sunnybank Inn</b> (828-622-7206).&Acirc;&nbsp;
Extremely popular with AT through hikers, a stay at Elmer&#39;s includes
a family-style vegetarian dinner and breakfast and a chance to converse
with an extremely eclectic assortment of guests.&Acirc;&nbsp; In a former
life Elmer was a Methodist minister at Duke University;&Acirc;&nbsp; his
library is extensive.&Acirc;&nbsp; Most find the Sunnybank Inn through
word of mouth.&Acirc;&nbsp; Here are some of those words:&Acirc;&nbsp;
<a href="http://www.google.com/search?hl=en&amp;q=sunnybank+inn+%22Elmer+Hall%22&amp;btnG=Google+Search" target="_blank">Google Search on Elmer and the Sunnybank
Inn</a>.&Acirc;&nbsp; And for the two of you who are chomping at the bit
for pricier accommodations, here are a couple <a href="http://www.frenchbroadriverfest.com/lodging.htm" target="_blank">additional Hot Springs lodging options</a>.
</p>
<p>
&Acirc;&nbsp;
</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="20%">
